@*
    PostQuantum.Hybrid playground — single page, anchor-link navigation.
    Phase 1 ships hero + "Why hybrid?" + backend transparency badge. Later
    phases fill in Live Demo, Rotation, Security Hygiene, Code, and Install.
*@

@page "/"
@rendermode RenderMode.InteractiveServer
@inject BackendInfoService Backend

<PageTitle>PostQuantum.Hybrid — interactive demo</PageTitle>

<header class="site-header">
    <div class="container header-inner">
        <a class="brand" href="#top">
            <span class="brand-name">PostQuantum.Hybrid</span>
            <span class="brand-tag">interactive demo</span>
        </a>
        <div class="backend-badge @(Backend.NativePqAvailable ? "badge-native" : "badge-fallback")"
             title="@Backend.DetailedLabel">
            Backend: <strong>@Backend.ShortLabel</strong>
        </div>
    </div>
</header>

<main id="top" class="container">

    <section class="hero">
        <h1>Hybrid post-quantum cryptography for .NET — in your browser.</h1>
        <p class="hero-sub">
            This page is the gold-standard reference for
            <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/PostQuantum.Hybrid">PostQuantum.Hybrid</a>.
            It leads with the <strong>recommended</strong> high-level API
            (<code>HybridEnvelope.Seal</code> / <code>Open</code>), then peels
            back the layers so you can see what production code should — and
            should not — look like.
        </p>
        <nav class="anchor-nav" aria-label="Page sections">
            <a href="#why">Why hybrid?</a>
            <a href="#demo">Live demo</a>
            <a href="#rotation">Key rotation</a>
            <a href="#hygiene">Security hygiene</a>
            <a href="#copy">Code you can copy</a>
            <a href="#install">Use this in your project</a>
        </nav>
        <p class="hero-meta">
            Native .NET 10 cryptography when supported by the host's OpenSSL;
            BouncyCastle fallback otherwise (see
            <a href="https://github.com/systemslibrarian/PostQuantum.Hybrid/blob/main/docs/adr/0012-runtime-backend-fallback.md">ADR&nbsp;0012</a>).
            This container reports <strong>@Backend.ShortLabel</strong>.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="why" class="band">
        <h2>Why hybrid?</h2>
        <p>
            Today's TLS protects key exchange with elliptic-curve Diffie-Hellman
            (X25519) and authentication with Ed25519 signatures. Both are safe
            against the attackers we actually have — but a sufficiently large
            quantum computer would break both in polynomial time (Shor's
            algorithm). NIST's <strong>ML-KEM-768</strong> (FIPS&nbsp;203) and
            <strong>ML-DSA-65</strong> (FIPS&nbsp;204) are post-quantum
            replacements that no known quantum algorithm breaks — but they are
            new, and the cryptographic community has had decades to scrutinize
            X25519 / Ed25519 that ML-KEM and ML-DSA have not yet had.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Hybrid construction</strong> sidesteps that asymmetry of
            confidence. PostQuantum.Hybrid runs both primitives in parallel and
            combines their outputs so the resulting shared secret (or
            signature) is safe as long as <em>either</em> primitive holds:
        </p>
        <div class="primitives">
            <div class="primitive">
                <h3>Hybrid KEM</h3>
                <p class="primitive-formula">X25519&nbsp;+&nbsp;ML-KEM-768</p>
                <p class="primitive-detail">
                    Two key encapsulations run side by side. The classical and
                    post-quantum shared secrets are mixed through HKDF-SHA256
                    with the KEM ciphertexts bound into the transcript, so an
                    attacker breaking just one primitive learns nothing.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="primitive">
                <h3>Hybrid signatures</h3>
                <p class="primitive-formula">Ed25519&nbsp;+&nbsp;ML-DSA-65</p>
                <p class="primitive-detail">
                    Two signatures are concatenated and BOTH must verify. A
                    forger needs to defeat both schemes simultaneously, which
                    is strictly harder than defeating either one alone.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <p>
            The library is fail-closed: every parse, verify, and decapsulate
            failure throws or returns <code>false</code>. There is no silent
            fallback to "best effort" mode. ML-KEM uses FIPS-203 implicit
            rejection, which means malformed ciphertexts yield a pseudorandom
            shared secret — the combined hybrid secret then diverges and the
            downstream AEAD authentically rejects.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="demo" class="band">
        <h2>Live demo</h2>
        <p>
            Three depths of API. The default — <strong>Recommended</strong> — is
            what new code should look like. The other tabs peel layers off so
            you can see exactly what the library does for you.
        </p>
        <LiveDemo />
        <p class="caveat">
            The crypto runs on the server. The Blazor Server interactive render
            mode means clicks call into <code>HybridEnvelope</code> directly
            without exposing private keys to your browser. If you want to drive
            the same operations from the shell, the JSON endpoints at
            <a href="/swagger" target="_blank" rel="noopener">/swagger</a>
            are wired through the same recommended path.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="rotation" class="band">
        <h2>Key rotation</h2>
        <p class="placeholder">
            Live <code>IRotatingHybridKemKeyProvider</code> visualization
            lands in Phase&nbsp;3. See
            <a href="https://github.com/systemslibrarian/PostQuantum.Hybrid/tree/main/samples/KeyRotationDemo"><code>samples/KeyRotationDemo</code></a>
            for the runnable script in the meantime.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="hygiene" class="band">
        <h2>Security hygiene</h2>
        <p class="placeholder">
            Live PQH001–PQH005 analyzer diagnostics from a deliberately-broken
            companion project land in Phase&nbsp;4.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="copy" class="band">
        <h2>Code you can copy</h2>
        <p class="placeholder">
            Polished snippets + copy buttons land in Phase&nbsp;5. For now,
            grab them from
            <a href="https://github.com/systemslibrarian/PostQuantum.Hybrid/tree/main/samples/EnvelopesDemo"><code>samples/EnvelopesDemo</code></a>.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="install" class="band">
        <h2>Use this in your project</h2>
        <p class="placeholder">
            Install commands, template references, and the "which package?"
            matrix land in Phase&nbsp;5.
        </p>
        <pre class="code">dotnet add package PostQuantum.Hybrid
dotnet add package PostQuantum.Hybrid.Envelopes
dotnet add package PostQuantum.Hybrid.Analyzers</pre>
    </section>

</main>

<footer class="site-footer">
    <div class="container footer-inner">
        <p>
            Source:
